<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1930-05-02T05:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1930-05-02T05:00:00-05:00" n="387" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d387">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">863.51 Relief Credits/221: Telegram</note>
                        <head><hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in Great Britain</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Dawes</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                                State</gloss></hi></head>
                        <opener><dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">London</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1930-05-02T11:00:00+01:00">May 2, 1930—11
                                a.m.</date><lb/>[Received May 2—6 a.m.]</dateline></opener>
                        <p>88. Department’s 93, April 15, 6 p.m. In letter dated May 1, 1930,
                            Foreign Office refers to the letter, dated April 16, 1930, sent <pb facs="0479" n="399" xml:id="pg_399"/> by Sir Frederick Leith-Ross to
                            the Austrian Minister (text of which was contained in Embassy’s 69,
                            April 17, 3 P.M.), and states: <quote rend="blockquote">
                                <p>“Sir Frederick Leith-Ross, besides being Chairman of the
                                    International Relief Bonds Committee, is of course the
                                    representative of His Majesty’s Government on the Committee and
                                    the letter which he wrote was written with their authority and
                                    embodies their intention.”</p>
                            </quote></p>
                        <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Dawes</hi></signed></closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>